explanation:
To decide whether the code in OS_BinSemGive violates the MISRA guideline that pointers should point to const-qualified types where possible, the analyzer must know whether the pointer parameters actually get modified or only read. Specifically:

- OS_ObjectIdGetById (declaration + implementation): The call passes &token to this function. You must inspect its prototype to see whether the parameter is a pointer-to-const or pointer-to-non-const and its implementation to determine whether it writes into the token (if it writes, the pointer must not be const).

- OS_BinSemGive_Impl (declaration + implementation): The call passes &token here as well. Its prototype shows whether it accepts a const-qualified pointer; its implementation (and callees) shows whether it mutates the token, which determines if the parameter should be non-const.

- OS_object_token_t (typedef / struct definition): The object whose address is taken. To reason about const-qualification you need the full type (and its members) to see if any fields are modified or if it contains internal pointer members that affect const correctness.

- osal_id_t (typedef) and int32 (typedef): Basic typedefs used in the function signature and return value; required for accurate prototype matching and to ensure correct interpretation of parameter usage (not pointers themselves but needed to inspect function declarations consistently).

- OS_ObjectIndexFromToken (declaration + implementation): Called by OS_BinSemGive_Impl per the call graph; may read or modify the token. If it modifies the token, then OS_BinSemGive_Impl cannot take a const pointer and, transitively, OS_BinSemGive's use of &token is justified as non-const.

- OS_Posix_BinSemAcquireMutex (declaration + implementation): Also called by OS_BinSemGive_Impl; include to see whether the token (or fields derived from it) are modified or only read, influencing const qualification decisions.

- OS_ObjectIdConvertToken (declaration + implementation): Called by OS_ObjectIdGetById (per call graph). Its behavior may be the place token is populated/modified; needed to establish whether OS_ObjectIdGetById writes into token (so token parameter cannot be const).

- OS_LOCK_MODE_NONE, LOCAL_OBJID_TYPE, OS_SUCCESS (macros/enums): These constants appear in the call to OS_ObjectIdGetById and in the return check. While they do not affect pointer constness directly, including them ensures the correct overload/prototype is selected and aids understanding of whether the call is an output operation (e.g., a get-by-id that fills token) versus a read-only query.

Include the declarations and (preferably) implementations of the listed functions so you can determine for each pointer parameter whether the pointed-to object is modified (necessitating a non-const pointer) or only read (in which case the parameter should be const per MISRA).
